  "prompt": "What happens to a photon after it hits the retina of my eye?",
  "response": "When a photon hits the retina of your eye, it interacts with the photoreceptor cells, specifically the rods and cones. Here\u2019s a step-by-step outline of what happens:\n\n1. **Photon Absorption**: The photon is absorbed by a photopigment molecule within the photoreceptor cells. In rods, this photopigment is called rhodopsin, while in cones, there are different photopigments sensitive to different wavelengths of light (color).\n\n2. **Phototransduction**: The absorption of the photon causes a conformational change in the photopigment molecule. For example, in rhodopsin, the change converts 11-cis-retinal to all-trans-retinal. This conformational shift activates a G-protein called transducin.\n\n3. **Cascade of Reactions**: The activated transducin then activates phosphodiesterase (PDE), which reduces the level of cyclic GMP (cGMP) in the photoreceptor cell.\n\n4. **Closing of Ion Channels**: The decrease in cGMP leads to the closure of cGMP-gated ion channels, which normally allow sodium (Na+) and calcium (Ca2+) ions to enter the cell. The closing of these channels results in hyperpolarization of the photoreceptor cell membrane.\n\n5. **Signal Transmission**: The hyperpolarization reduces the release of the neurotransmitter glutamate from the photoreceptor cell. This change in neurotransmitter release is detected by bipolar cells in the retina.\n\n6. **Processing by Retinal Cells**: Bipolar cells transmit the signal to ganglion cells, which then send action potentials through their axons. These axons converge to form the optic nerve.\n\n7. **Optic Nerve to Brain**: The optic nerve carries the visual information to the brain, specifically to the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) of the thalamus, and subsequently to the visual cortex in the occipital lobe.\n\n8. **Perception**: The brain processes the information received from the retina, leading to the perception of the image.\n\nIn summary, the photon\u2019s energy initiates a complex biochemical process within the retina that ultimately results in electrical signals being sent to the brain, allowing you to perceive light and images.",
